== Dharma Talk on Trekchö and Tögal 

When you get into Dzogchen, and these practices can be found in other approaches, these are ancient, timeless practices... there are generally two sections that get associated: that's Trekchö and Tögal, as they're called. Trekchö is being introduced to this very simple awareness and beginning to use that awareness to cut through conditioning. So just having awareness of thoughts, just starting to get used to the mindfulness or the awareness aspect is very, very beneficial because you're already starting to get out of your thoughts and into a cognition that supersedes thoughts.

The Tögal aspect, in my opinion, has been systematized almost inappropriately. There are many yogis that do Tögal, and in my opinion, Tögal began to come naturally to the yogi. Tögal practices deal with phenomena, with appearances, sounds, all sense---the whole sense world. We're starting to integrate that into our awareness practice, and that's the Tögal aspect. And the idea here is that this entire reality is actually made out of a kind of smart light.

This light is smart because it can crystallize, it can be hardened, or it can be softened. And it can be blended and fashioned into things like mountains and all kinds of stuff that we agree on in a collective. The sun and the moon are beautiful paintings of the mind. And so we all have the same body, we all have a sun and a moon, and all these planets and all the space. 

We all have that same body, but we paint it different. The ants look at the sun and they see something else, but that's still part of their body. The wolf howls at the moon, or the coyotes howling at the moon, to them, their body is painted different. Just like the Navajo, you know, they say that we can paint ourselves.

And so sometimes we paint very, very pretty pictures, and we get lost in our own paintings. Sometimes we paint angry pictures, and we go to war with our own paintings. And then because of karma, we meet somebody who's also painting an angry picture. So we're constantly battling, I'm sorry to say, if you're mad at somebody right now, you're mad at your own mind. If you're worried, if you're confused, you're worried about your own mind.

So Trekchö and Tögal are these two main aspects: awareness in my body, in my experience. Awareness in the environment. Trekchö, Tögal come together, and that is the Dzogchen Samatha-Vipassanā.

Now there's natural cutting through happening. Awareness is... if you get upset, awareness is there with you, cutting through. If you get hooked on sense stimulation, "Oh, I really, I love that piece of pizza, that apple or something", awareness is cutting through now, because you've been introduced. 

Now it's very, very, very difficult to even entertain the possibility that our environment is mind. So that's why Tögal can be highly beneficial, but I wouldn't prioritize it over everything, the way that they do. I believe it's only really the Yeshé Lama, and now you can kind of get in trouble for just saying that. But I think there's... even the Yeshé Lama tells you, that there's this kind of phase that goes beyond Tögal and Trekchö. 

So that's a little technical information on this, okay? Dzogchen just has a very systematized way to approach liberation. They're making sure that your mind doesn't trick you by introducing Trekchö and Tögal.
 
And Tögal, typically has these postures associated with it, because if I sit here in normal posture while I'm eating a sandwich, I may not see bindus, light rays, orbs, all kinds of decrystallization within my reifications. I may not even pick up on that, because I'm eating the sandwich, I'm hunkered down into my constructions. 

But if I'm in one of the three postures, the elephant, lion, or the rishi Tögal postures, now I'm making it so karma cannot clog up in my empty channels. And so I'm opening my eyes and doing this squinting a little bit and pulling the ray off of the light source, and seeing the bindus. This is a constant practice that they do. And now that's allowed to happen, now I can see the bindus because I'm in that posture. Okay, so that's why they have the three postures of Tögal. 

But we're approaching this a little bit different. We're not utilizing those three postures, and we're not going into Trekchö proper or Tögal proper. We're doing a Dzogchen Samatha-Vipassanā with the introduction to clear light. 

So that's what I invite everybody to do now. Relax a little bit and we'll do a sort of Samatha-Vipassanā-Tögal. 

So as you have your eyes open, just let them fall into empty space, right? Just let them relax without focusing on anything. Now let three things be in your vision in awareness, just three things, let them stand out a little bit. For me it would be the laptop, the phone, and a drum. Anybody not know what I mean by picking three things and letting it just be there in your vision? You got that, right? 

Notice how... just let them be in your presence for a second, let those three things just be in the presence of your mind.

Notice how the body is also in this presence of mind, the whole body. And the space in between has a presence of mind. All three objects are permeated by that presence of the mind. And you see, there's a clear light, very subtle presence of your mind holding the three objects. 

Making sense? Any questions about that? Anybody not noticing the presence of their mind in the environment? 

You can actually shift to where there is no feeling of referentiality, there's only the subtle presence. So that's really it, you're noticing the clear light, very subtle presence, and then the objects naturally being held within that presence.

[Yote gets very excited about Tögal]. "Hi Yote, say woo woo." She said it really quietly. Okay, any questions? 

All right, it's just about recognizing. It may seem very, very obvious, but we don't explicitly acknowledge, yeah these things are naturally held within the knowingness of my mind. 

Okay, that's all I got. Very good. And so yes, you can get fancy and start to do these light practices and everything, but I think it's much more direct to just begin to familiarize with outside of your body. Because the whole body, every emotion that you could ever have, is in that space just like the object. My body, all my thoughts, whether I'm having a profound meditation or a stupid meditation, it's all sitting here just like the drum is sitting here. Whether the drum is being played or not, that drum is just within space-like awareness. 

So why do we get caught up in it? The drum's playing, the drum's not playing. We care so much about our experiences. Today I had a good meditation, today I had a bad meditation, it's the same as saying the drum is playing, the drum's not playing, it's all just sitting there within awareness. 

So we're not really concerned with meditation experiences: having an experience of enlightenment. That's not it. And that's how it's self-protected, that's how it's self-secret. There is no experience of enlightenment. 

